          <li>â€¢ Testing a business idea</li>
          <li>â€¢ Temporary landing page</li>
          <li>â€¢ Student/Personal project</li>
          <li>â€¢ You have zero budget</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-xs text-green-600 mt-4">Note: Upgrade when you earn $100+ or need professional features.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-red-50 border-[3px] border-red-400 rounded-xl p-6">
        <p class="font-bold text-red-800 mb-2">âœ— Don't Use Free Tier If...</p>
        <ul class="text-sm space-y-1 mt-2">
          <li>â€¢ Client work (looks unprofessional)</li>
          <li>â€¢ E-commerce (limits kill conversions)</li>
          <li>â€¢ Long-term project (you'll migrate anyway)</li>
          <li>â€¢ SEO matters (subdomains rank worse)</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="text-xs text-red-600 mt-4">Note: The $15/month saves you hours of pain and lost revenue.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-black mb-6">The "Freemium" Strategy Explained</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Why do AI builders offer free tiers? It's not charity. It's a calculated business strategy called "freemium"â€”give away a limited version to hook users, then convert them to paying customers.
      </p>

      <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        <strong>The math works like this:</strong> For every 100 free users, 3-5 convert to paid. Those paying customers subsidize the free ones. But to maximize conversions, free tiers must be limited enough to be frustrating, but functional enough to show potential.
      </p>

      <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        <strong>The result:</strong> Free tiers are designed to push you toward upgrades. Page limits, storage limits, feature gatesâ€”these aren't technical constraints, they're business decisions. You're supposed to hit the wall and pay.
      </p>

      <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        <strong>Is this bad?</strong> No, it's smart business. But understand what you're getting into. Free tiers are marketing tools, not products. Use them accordingly.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-3xl font-black mb-6">When to Upgrade from Free</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Don't wait until free tiers break your workflow. Upgrade proactively when:
      </p>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        <div class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-500 p-4">
          <p class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">You're earning revenue</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-700">If your site makes $100+/month, the cheapest paid plan pays for itself. The ROI is immediate. Don't hamper revenue-generating features to save $15.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-500 p-4">
          <p class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">You need a custom domain</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-700">Free tiers lock you to subdomains. For serious projects, a custom domain is table stakes. Branding, trust, SEOâ€”all suffer on builder subdomains.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-500 p-4">
          <p class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">You're hitting feature limits</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-700">Need more than 2-3 pages? Want to remove builder branding? Running out of storage? These are signs you've outgrown free tiers.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-blue-50 border-l-4 border-blue-500 p-4">
          <p class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">You're doing client work</p>
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-700">Builder branding on client sites makes you look amateur. Clients pay for professionalismâ€”show it with a paid plan.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

